    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Representing length to a given scale}</m> involves creating a proportional representation of real-world measurements, typically in drawings, maps, or models.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{A scale}</m> is a ratio that compares the dimensions of a representation (like a drawing) to the corresponding dimensions of the actual object. It indicates how much smaller or larger the representation is compared to reality.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The length of a school field is measured as <m>12000 \textbf{ cm}</m>. Given that <m>1 \textbf{ cm}</m> represents <m>600 \textbf{ cm}</m>, represent the length of the school field on paper.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Actual length of a school field = <m>12000 \textbf{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Scale = <m>1 \textbf{ cm}</m> represents <m>600 \textbf{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                To find the length on paper, we use the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{Drawing Length} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Actual Length}}{\textbf{Scale Factor}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{12,000}{600}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 20 \textbf{ cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, The length of the school field on paper will be <m>20 \textbf{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The height of a mountain is <m>3,500 \textbf{ meters}</m>. If we use a scale where <m>1 \textbf{ cm}</m> represents <m>500 \textbf{ meters}</m>, represent the height of the mountain in your workbook.
            </p>

        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Actual height of the mountain = <m>3500 \textbf{ meters}</m> 
            </p>
            <p>
                Scale = <m>1 \textbf{ cm}</m> represents <m>500 \textbf{ meters}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                To find the height of the mountain on paper, we use the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{Drawing Height} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Actual height }}{\textbf{Scale factor}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{3500}{500}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =  \amp 7 \textbf{ cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            
            <p>
                Therefore, the height of the mountain would be drawn as <m>7 \textbf{ cm}</m> tall on paper.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A map has a scale of <m>1:75,000</m>. A road is <m>6 \textbf{ kilometers}</m> long in reality. How long should it be drawn on the map in centimeters?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Scale = <m>1:75,000</m> (This means <m>1 \textbf{ cm}</m> on the map represents <m>75,000 \textbf{ cm}</m> in reality.)
            </p>
            <p>
                Actual road length = <m>6 \textbf{ km}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Convert kilometers to centimeters:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp \frac{6 \cancel{ km}}{1 \cancel{ km}} \times 100,000 \textbf{ cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 600,000\textbf{ cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, we use the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{Drawing Length} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Actual Length}}{\textbf{Scale Factor}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{600,000}{75,000}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 8 \textbf{ cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The road should be drawn as <m>8 \textbf{ cm}</m> long on the map.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
</subsection>